<div class="page-shell">
  <header class="topbar">
    <a class="brand" href="/">
      <img class="brand-mark" src="/icons/app-icon.svg" alt="Inkcreate icon">
      <span class="brand-copy">
        <strong>Inkcreate</strong>
        <span>Notebook OCR Companion</span>
      </span>
    </a>

    <div class="topbar-right">
      <nav aria-label="Landing sections">
        <a href="#why">Why it works</a>
        <a href="#flow">Workflow</a>
      </nav>

      <div class="nav-actions <%= "nav-actions-auth" unless user_signed_in? %>">
        <% if user_signed_in? %>
          <a class="mini-button mini-button-primary" href="<%= dashboard_path %>">Open workspace</a>
        <% else %>
          <a class="mini-button" href="<%= browser_sign_in_path %>">Sign in</a>
          <a class="mini-button mini-button-primary" href="<%= browser_sign_up_path %>">Create account</a>
        <% end %>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="hero">
    <article class="hero-copy">
      <div class="eyebrow">Mobile-first capture for handwritten notes</div>
      <h1>Turn notebook pages into structured, searchable records.</h1>
      <p>
        Inkcreate is built for the messy reality of real notebooks: angled photos,
        recurring page templates, OCR that needs background processing, and exports
        that should land cleanly in Google Drive without manual cleanup.
      </p>

      <% if user_signed_in? %>
        <div class="cta-row">
          <a class="button button-primary" href="<%= dashboard_path %>">Open workspace</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="#flow">See the workflow</a>
        </div>
      <% end %>

      <div class="stat-row">
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="mini-label">Capture</div>
          <strong>Direct uploads to cloud storage</strong>
        </div>
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="mini-label">Extract</div>
          <strong>Async OCR with template-aware processing</strong>
        </div>
        <div class="stat">
          <div class="mini-label">Ship</div>
          <strong>Searchable records and Drive-ready exports</strong>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <aside class="hero-stack" aria-label="Product workflow preview">
      <div class="paper-column">
        <article class="paper">
          <span class="paper-accent"></span>
          <div class="mini-label">01 Scan</div>
          <h3>Capture pages in motion</h3>
          <p>Phone-first uploads keep the flow fast even when pages are skewed, shadowed, or mid-session.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="paper">
          <span class="paper-accent"></span>
          <div class="mini-label">02 Classify</div>
          <h3>Recognize the template</h3>
          <p>Page patterns and notebook metadata help the OCR pipeline understand what kind of page just arrived.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="paper">
          <span class="paper-accent"></span>
          <div class="mini-label">03 Extract</div>
          <h3>Normalize the text</h3>
          <p>Background jobs keep extraction out of the request path so the experience stays responsive.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="paper">
          <span class="paper-accent"></span>
          <div class="mini-label">04 Export</div>
          <h3>Push the result where it belongs</h3>
          <p>Search, tags, and Google Drive export turn a pile of page photos into something you can actually use.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </aside>
  </section>

  <main>
    <section class="section-card" id="why">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">Why it works</div>
        <h2>Built for notebook chaos, not lab-perfect OCR samples.</h2>
        <p>
          The product is shaped around real capture behavior: quick uploads from mobile,
          structured storage, resilient async jobs, and enough metadata to recover meaning
          after the image leaves the camera roll.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="feature-grid">
        <article class="feature-card">
          <div class="pill">Same-origin sessions</div>
          <h3>Secure by default</h3>
          <p>
            Cookie-based sessions and CSRF protection keep auth simple for a same-origin
            web app without bolting on a second identity layer.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="feature-card">
          <div class="pill">Background OCR</div>
          <h3>Responsive under load</h3>
          <p>
            OCR and Drive sync work leaves the request cycle quickly, so uploads stay fast
            while Sidekiq or Cloud Tasks handle the expensive work behind the scenes.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="feature-card">
          <div class="pill">Structured records</div>
          <h3>Searchable after capture</h3>
          <p>
            Notebook, tag, and capture models give the extracted text a real home instead
            of treating each image as an isolated blob.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-card" id="flow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">Workflow</div>
        <h2>From photo to usable note in four deliberate steps.</h2>
        <p>
          The pipeline is intentionally simple to follow: ingest, queue, extract, and deliver.
          That makes it easier to scale the heavy parts without turning the product into a black box.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="flow">
        <article class="flow-step">
          <div class="mini-label">Step 1</div>
          <strong>Upload the page</strong>
          <p>The client requests a signed upload URL and sends the original image straight to storage.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="flow-step">
          <div class="mini-label">Step 2</div>
          <strong>Create the capture</strong>
          <p>Inkcreate stores the notebook context, template hints, and OCR provider settings for the page.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="flow-step">
          <div class="mini-label">Step 3</div>
          <strong>Run OCR asynchronously</strong>
          <p>Workers preprocess the image, run extraction, and attach structured results without blocking the user.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="flow-step">
          <div class="mini-label">Step 4</div>
          <strong>Search or export</strong>
          <p>Clean text becomes available for search, reprocessing, tagging, and Drive export when needed.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

  </main>

  <%= render "shared/public_footer" %>
</div>
